{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567479"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:02:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:02:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19053"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19053"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.46,0.04,0.01,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106294"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88762"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8204"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45770"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106294"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive fatigue, mild weight gain of 3 kg, and cold intolerance. She reports difficulty concentrating at work and mild constipation. She has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her regular medications are amlodipine and atorvastatin. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 58/min, blood pressure 145/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.2\u00b0C. Her thyroid gland is not palpably enlarged. Cardiovascular examination reveals a regular rhythm with no murmurs. Her deep tendon reflexes show mildly delayed relaxation phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone: 12.8 mU/L (0.4-4.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFree thyroxine (T4): 11 pmol/L (10-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThyroid peroxidase antibodies: 180 IU/mL (\u0026lt;35)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal cholesterol: 6.8 mmol/L (\u0026lt;5.2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EElectrocardiogram: sinus bradycardia, rate 58/min, normal intervals\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence levothyroxine 25 micrograms daily","Commence levothyroxine 100 micrograms daily","Repeat thyroid function tests in six months","Commence liothyronine 10 micrograms daily","Refer for thyroid ultrasound before treatment"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with subclinical hypothyroidism (elevated TSH with normal free T4) in the setting of positive thyroid peroxidase antibodies, indicating autoimmune thyroiditis. The TSH level of 12.8 mU/L, combined with symptomatic presentation and cardiovascular risk factors, supports the decision to initiate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing levothyroxine 25 micrograms daily\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for this older patient with cardiovascular comorbidities. The lower starting dose reduces the risk of precipitating cardiac arrhythmias or angina, while still providing therapeutic benefit. The dose can be titrated upward based on TSH response and symptom improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing levothyroxine 100 micrograms daily\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for subclinical hypothyroidism, particularly in an older patient with cardiovascular disease. This higher dose increases the risk of cardiac complications and is typically reserved for younger patients with overt hypothyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating thyroid function tests in six months\u003C/strong\u003E without treatment would be inappropriate given the significantly elevated TSH above 10 mU/L, presence of symptoms, and positive antibodies indicating progressive autoimmune disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing liothyronine 10 micrograms daily\u003C/strong\u003E is not first-line therapy. Liothyronine has a shorter half-life, requires multiple daily doses, and can cause more cardiac side effects. It is reserved for specific indications where levothyroxine is ineffective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for thyroid ultrasound before treatment\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary and inappropriate. The combination of elevated TSH, positive thyroid antibodies, and clinical presentation is diagnostic for autoimmune hypothyroidism. Ultrasound would not change the management approach and would delay appropriate treatment; it may also cause harm through unexpected findings requiring further investigation and potentially invasive management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subclinical hypothyroidism with symptoms warrants treatment consideration, particularly when TSH is persistently above 10 mU/L.","Levothyroxine dosing in subclinical hypothyroidism should start lower than in overt hypothyroidism, typically 25-50 micrograms daily.","Cardiovascular risk factors influence the decision to treat subclinical hypothyroidism and require careful monitoring during treatment initiation."],"references":["Croker EE, McGrath SA, Rowe CW. Thyroid disease: Using diagnostic tools effectively. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021 Jan-Feb;50(1-2):16-21. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/january-february/thyroid-disease-using-diagnostic-tools-effectively"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88762"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19053"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88762"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T18:16:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T18:16:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11787"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106294"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"d